WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.895 --> 00:00:03.145
NICK JANKEL: Great to be here.

00:00:03.145 --> 00:00:06.180
I'm very privileged to
share some ideas with you.

00:00:06.180 --> 00:00:10.100
I'm going to give you the top
slice of about 20 years work

00:00:10.100 --> 00:00:13.290
as a committed
philosopher, thinker.

00:00:13.290 --> 00:00:15.840
And I spent 16 years
as an entrepreneur.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:18.450
I started my first company
when I was 24 in London

00:00:18.450 --> 00:00:20.390
after reading "The
Cluetrain Manifesto,"

00:00:20.390 --> 00:00:22.930
and realizing that all
markets are conversations,

00:00:22.930 --> 00:00:24.740
they're not full of consumers.

00:00:24.740 --> 00:00:28.710
And that created a whole
wave of innovation for me.

00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:32.540
This is part talk,
part experience,

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:36.370
and it's based around the
book I've just published,

00:00:36.370 --> 00:00:41.030
which you've got a copy
of, which is great.

00:00:41.030 --> 00:00:43.830
And it's about how to have
and sustain breakthroughs

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:47.250
in yourself, your life, but
also in your enterprise.

00:00:47.250 --> 00:00:49.370
And hopefully,
inspiring you to look

00:00:49.370 --> 00:00:51.670
at how to break through
problems in the world,

00:00:51.670 --> 00:00:54.310
really connecting my
change as an individual

00:00:54.310 --> 00:00:57.461
with the changes we want to
see out there in the world.

00:00:57.461 --> 00:00:59.710
I'll give you bit more about
my life and my background

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:01.210
as we go along.

00:01:01.210 --> 00:01:03.920
But as you're
Googlers, super smart,

00:01:03.920 --> 00:01:08.350
I'm going to give you a
little question, a challenge.

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:14.305
So put your hand up when you
have solved this anagram.

00:01:26.171 --> 00:01:26.920
Come on, Googlers.

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:34.190
OK, we've got one.

00:01:38.164 --> 00:01:39.740
A couple more.

00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:41.820
Another one.

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:42.320
All right.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:44.482
Do you want to share it with us?

00:01:44.482 --> 00:01:45.190
AUDIENCE: Cubism?

00:01:45.190 --> 00:01:46.220
NICK JANKEL: Cubism.

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:48.340
Right.

00:01:48.340 --> 00:01:51.537
About 30 people, not
many got it, right?

00:01:51.537 --> 00:01:53.870
Actually, you're actually one
of the highest percentages

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:56.340
I've ever seen in a group.

00:01:56.340 --> 00:02:00.240
Usually 1%, 2% of the group get,
OK, in a short period of time.

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:03.740
Whose brain, whose mind
was saying, over and over,

00:02:03.740 --> 00:02:04.894
"Be music, be music"?

00:02:04.894 --> 00:02:06.060
All right, put your hand up.

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:06.910
Let me know.

00:02:06.910 --> 00:02:07.780
Right.

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:09.800
That gives you a glimpse
of the challenges

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:12.740
we face as human beings
about how to break through.

00:02:12.740 --> 00:02:14.660
Because our mind likes
to hold on to what

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:19.430
we can see now, rather than take
the risk to go and embrace what

00:02:19.430 --> 00:02:20.475
might be.

00:02:20.475 --> 00:02:23.710
And we'll come back to that
theme as we go throughout.

00:02:23.710 --> 00:02:25.700
A little background about me.

00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:28.564
Started my career in
medicine, studying medicine,

00:02:28.564 --> 00:02:29.730
wanted to be a psychiatrist.

00:02:29.730 --> 00:02:32.280
And then flipped into
philosophy of science.

00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:34.630
Long story, I won't
give it to you now.

00:02:34.630 --> 00:02:36.214
I came out of
philosophy of science

00:02:36.214 --> 00:02:39.600
with a good grounding in
social theory, human sciences,

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:41.070
and natural sciences.

00:02:41.070 --> 00:02:43.470
And naturally, I go into
advertising, working

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:45.910
for a very large ad agency,
working with PlayStation,

00:02:45.910 --> 00:02:48.350
mainly, my first big client,
when they were very young.

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:50.060
And we helped grow them.

00:02:50.060 --> 00:02:53.200
As I said, 1999, I read
"The Cluetrain Manifesto."

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:54.700
I saw the digital
wave and was like,

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:57.199
I've got to get up on this wave,
because ad agencies are not

00:02:57.199 --> 00:02:58.150
on it at all.

00:02:58.150 --> 00:03:02.620
Started up a tech-friendly
startup accelerator

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:04.800
mixed with marketing,
brand consultancy.

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:07.910
We then pivoted when
that industry dried up.

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:10.715
We pivoted in 2001 to
become an innovation agency,

00:03:10.715 --> 00:03:13.340
working with many of the largest
companies in the world on very

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:16.570
big projects to develop
7, 10 year products

00:03:16.570 --> 00:03:18.550
services, et cetera.

00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:20.640
For reasons I will give
you a bit later on,

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:22.242
I then got into
social innovation more

00:03:22.242 --> 00:03:24.075
than commercial innovation,
although the two

00:03:24.075 --> 00:03:26.094
have become really
nicely connected

00:03:26.094 --> 00:03:27.510
at the moment,
which is beautiful,

00:03:27.510 --> 00:03:30.890
as more companies realize they
want to solve big problems, not

00:03:30.890 --> 00:03:34.270
just small little
widget problems.

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:38.410
And I realized over 15
years of doing this work,

00:03:38.410 --> 00:03:42.790
that leadership, empowerment,
individual psychology

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:46.339
and being, is actually the most
important thing in innovation.

00:03:46.339 --> 00:03:48.130
So I ended up getting
into leadership work.

00:03:48.130 --> 00:03:50.380
I did a lot of leadership
work with large companies.

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:53.280
And then have finally
come into myself

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:55.660
as a wisdom teacher,
which is a very posh term.

00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:56.570
I didn't really hear about
it until a few years ago.

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:58.445
I was like, yes, that
sounds like something I

00:03:58.445 --> 00:04:01.440
do-- teaching people how
to thrive in the world.

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:04.000
Which as you can see,
kind of came full circle

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.220
to my first initial desire to be
psychiatrist when I was 15, 16.

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:11.180
It's been a long
journey, not an easy one.

00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:14.950
And I'll share a few
insights from my journey.

00:04:14.950 --> 00:04:17.550
So what connects all
my work-- so I work

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:19.200
with very large organizations.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:23.190
I've worked with Number 10,
I've worked with the European

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:25.310
Commission, and then
working with individuals

00:04:25.310 --> 00:04:26.537
on their own life.

00:04:26.537 --> 00:04:28.870
What connects them, is my
understanding of breakthrough,

00:04:28.870 --> 00:04:31.860
which I have recently coined
the term "Breakthrough

00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:34.722
Biodynamics," and hopefully
you understand why,

00:04:34.722 --> 00:04:36.930
by the end of this talk,
why it's biodynamics and not

00:04:36.930 --> 00:04:39.090
just dynamics.

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:40.650
So that's what holds
it all together.

00:04:40.650 --> 00:04:44.640
I run three different
parts of that, if you,

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:47.350
like three strands, three
flavors of ice cream.

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:49.370
The first, as myself
as a teacher, author,

00:04:49.370 --> 00:04:53.880
and I did a couple of TV shows
as a present, more in the way.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:55.675
I run this innovation,
Conscious Innovation

00:04:55.675 --> 00:04:57.470
and Leadership Consultancy.

00:04:57.470 --> 00:05:00.580
And recently, about a year
ago, set up a new media

00:05:00.580 --> 00:05:04.120
company, kind of like the vice
magazine of positive wisdom

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:04.790
content.

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:06.206
That's the kind
of idea behind it.

00:05:06.206 --> 00:05:06.750
So big idea.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:08.279
Biggest idea I've ever had.

00:05:08.279 --> 00:05:10.570
So check that out if you're
interested in wisdom, world

00:05:10.570 --> 00:05:13.100
change, and well-being content.

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:16.820
And if anyone wants offer
their awesome Google ninjutsu,

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:18.940
I would love to hear.

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:22.300
Because creating a digital
content company in this world

00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:24.800
is quite a trip.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:26.240
So, over to you.

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:29.840
If you could break through
anything today in the next hour

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:32.550
of your lives--
anything at all--

00:05:32.550 --> 00:05:34.000
have a think what it would be.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:35.060
Don't tell anyone.

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:37.350
This is not a sharing session.

00:05:37.350 --> 00:05:39.792
Just have a think--
what would it be?

00:05:39.792 --> 00:05:41.500
It could be personal,
it could be career,

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:44.300
it could be a work thing, it
could be a business problem

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:47.022
that you're tasked to face.

00:05:47.022 --> 00:05:49.230
Another way of asking that
question is, where are you

00:05:49.230 --> 00:05:52.880
feeling stuck or
stressed-- something

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:56.579
you can't quite seem to work
out how to get through it?

00:05:56.579 --> 00:05:58.370
Or, another way of
asking the same question

00:05:58.370 --> 00:05:59.750
is, where can you
see an opportunity,

00:05:59.750 --> 00:06:02.095
but you haven't worked out
how to seize the opportunity?

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:06.620
Just have a think of
what that would be.

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:08.350
Go live.

00:06:08.350 --> 00:06:11.520
Don't do the dress
rehearsal of life.

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:13.060
Let's take it down right now.

00:06:13.060 --> 00:06:14.720
So have that in
your mind as we go

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:17.960
through the rest of
this conversation.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:19.330
So what is a breakthrough?

00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:20.309
It's a big word.

00:06:20.309 --> 00:06:22.100
People use the word
"disruptive innovation"

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:24.710
as one way of calling
it a breakthrough.

00:06:24.710 --> 00:06:27.200
"Epiphany" would be a
personal version of that.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:30.090
So just a few examples
to get us in the mood.

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:34.400
So here's a painting, a sort
of Zenith of western realist

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:35.730
painting.

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:36.730
Happens to be about war.

00:06:36.730 --> 00:06:38.820
And then this guy
came along and said,

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:43.871
well, what if we did a
painting about war like that?

00:06:43.871 --> 00:06:45.370
And what's interesting
to me is, you

00:06:45.370 --> 00:06:47.740
could spend your whole life
getting better and better

00:06:47.740 --> 00:06:52.640
at painting a
realistic image of war,

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:55.010
and never come up with that.

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:57.970
It's not a better
painting, to most people,

00:06:57.970 --> 00:06:59.786
certainly at the time.

00:06:59.786 --> 00:07:01.910
But this is one that's
famous, the other one isn't.

00:07:01.910 --> 00:07:03.990
This is one that's
worth gazillions,

00:07:03.990 --> 00:07:05.345
the other one isn't.

00:07:05.345 --> 00:07:06.720
So it's something
to think about.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:10.350
In its time, as many
breakthrough creators find,

00:07:10.350 --> 00:07:12.680
they're not appreciated
as much as they are when

00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:14.246
life and the world moves on.

00:07:14.246 --> 00:07:16.120
And we'll come on to
why that is in a minute.

00:07:16.120 --> 00:07:17.286
Here's another breakthrough.

00:07:17.286 --> 00:07:21.170
This is Newton's cradle, basic
understanding of how physics

00:07:21.170 --> 00:07:23.430
works, Newtonian mechanics.

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:26.780
Everyone familiar with
Newtonian mechanics, vaguely?

00:07:26.780 --> 00:07:29.780
Basically, if you hit one
ball to another, it moves.

00:07:29.780 --> 00:07:32.501
And then this came
along-- quantum theory.

00:07:32.501 --> 00:07:34.750
Schrodinger's cat, et cetera,
Heisenberg's Uncertainty

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:37.640
Principle, which has now
shifted fundamentally on how

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:39.550
everything in the world works.

00:07:39.550 --> 00:07:41.860
I'm sure some of you
in quantum computing,

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:44.720
quantum biology, which is
fascinating stuff going

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:45.690
on there.

00:07:45.690 --> 00:07:47.877
This kind of stuff is
happening all over the world.

00:07:47.877 --> 00:07:50.000
It was a total breakthrough.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.070
And even now, when
the scientists come up

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:54.010
with new ideas,
a bit of research

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:57.010
came out two years ago,
that out of 24 Nobel Prize

00:07:57.010 --> 00:08:00.820
winners for science, all 24
had had their papers rejected

00:08:00.820 --> 00:08:03.320
by scientific journals
for the discoveries

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:06.360
that they later went on
to win the Nobel Prize.

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:10.150
That's the highest echelon of
breakthrough-- the resistance

00:08:10.150 --> 00:08:12.030
from the existing
world to what you're

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.065
trying to bring into, right?

00:08:14.065 --> 00:08:15.440
And the resistance
from yourself,

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:16.830
which we'll come on to.

00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:17.960
Anyone know what this is?

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:22.680
Anyone know?

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:23.530
Anyone know?

00:08:23.530 --> 00:08:24.900
AUDIENCE: A video recorder?

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:28.660
NICK JANKEL: The first
ever digital camera.

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:29.510
I know.

00:08:29.510 --> 00:08:31.950
A kind of ghetto-blasted
looking camera.

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:32.679
Invented by?

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:36.559
Kodak.

00:08:36.559 --> 00:08:37.990
This guy.

00:08:37.990 --> 00:08:41.049
This says it already-- "My
prototype was big as a toaster.

00:08:41.049 --> 00:08:42.630
The technical people loved it.

00:08:42.630 --> 00:08:44.430
But it was film-less
photography.

00:08:44.430 --> 00:08:46.580
So management's reaction
was, that's cute.

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:49.040
But don't tell anyone about it."

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:51.690
Why is that?

00:08:51.690 --> 00:08:52.190
Why?

00:08:52.190 --> 00:08:53.529
AUDIENCE: They sell film.

00:08:53.529 --> 00:08:54.320
NICK JANKEL: Right.

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:55.464
This model-- it's film.

00:08:55.464 --> 00:08:56.130
What about film?

00:08:56.130 --> 00:09:00.270
Who's printed a photo
out in the last year?

00:09:00.270 --> 00:09:02.985
Who's printed out more than 100?

00:09:02.985 --> 00:09:03.875
Hmm.

00:09:03.875 --> 00:09:06.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:07.930
NICK JANKEL: Seeing a
collage, a big collage.

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:08.830
So one person.

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:12.560
You can't run a multinational
Fortune 50 company

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:15.820
based upon one person using
film to any great degree.

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:17.220
Right?

00:09:17.220 --> 00:09:20.710
These guys came along, and
many others, and totally

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:22.580
broke through the
industry of imagery.

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:26.880
Because they understood where
value lies in the emerging

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:29.610
future, not the past.

00:09:29.610 --> 00:09:31.900
And they weren't
held back by being

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:33.650
in digital-- in
film photography,

00:09:33.650 --> 00:09:36.520
in the film business, rather
than the image business.

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:40.490
Instagram is in the
image-sharing business.

00:09:40.490 --> 00:09:43.070
Kodak was in the
printing business.

00:09:43.070 --> 00:09:43.945
Very different thing.

00:09:43.945 --> 00:09:47.320
But what's fascinating to me
is, Kodak had all the MBAs, all

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:49.630
the resources, all the
money, the cash part, access

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:53.090
to the city, access to
Wall Street, consultants,

00:09:53.090 --> 00:09:58.100
ad agencies, and these
guys had nothing.

00:09:58.100 --> 00:10:01.790
So it's become very clear to
me that power in the present,

00:10:01.790 --> 00:10:03.290
does not always
lead to breakthrough

00:10:03.290 --> 00:10:05.896
innovation in the future.

00:10:05.896 --> 00:10:08.020
And of course, we're standing
in a company that has

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:10.520
massive power in the present.

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:12.270
It is an interesting
conversation to have,

00:10:12.270 --> 00:10:15.094
because if I'd done this
talk at Kodak 20 years ago,

00:10:15.094 --> 00:10:16.510
people would be,
what do you mean?

00:10:16.510 --> 00:10:17.551
We're the market leaders.

00:10:17.551 --> 00:10:18.935
We have been for 50 years.

00:10:18.935 --> 00:10:21.410
It's fascinating.

00:10:21.410 --> 00:10:24.140
Another example of this, Hilton,
the world's largest hotel

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:25.130
group.

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:27.390
Airbnb.

00:10:27.390 --> 00:10:30.136
Could have been started
by Hilton, easily.

00:10:30.136 --> 00:10:33.289
And look at this, though,
look at the market cap.

00:10:33.289 --> 00:10:34.330
This is a few months ago.

00:10:34.330 --> 00:10:37.270
It's actually now
even closer to Hilton.

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:42.690
But what really interests me
is this-- 300,000 employees,

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:45.280
versus 600 employees.

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:48.200
And nothing stopped
Hilton creating Airbnb.

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:48.700
Nothing.

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:50.741
There was no one with a
gun to their head saying,

00:10:50.741 --> 00:10:55.670
no way can you do
a sharing business.

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:57.420
So why is this happening?

00:10:57.420 --> 00:11:00.130
Why are breakthroughs not
coming from companies with all

00:11:00.130 --> 00:11:02.710
these smarts and all the money?

00:11:02.710 --> 00:11:04.965
And then how does this
play out in the real world

00:11:04.965 --> 00:11:06.200
of people and human beings?

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:08.020
Well, you can imagine
going to prison

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:10.500
has been quite a
challenging experience.

00:11:10.500 --> 00:11:13.800
This guy, famously,
was there for 27 years

00:11:13.800 --> 00:11:15.274
and said this about it.

00:11:15.274 --> 00:11:16.940
If I had not been in
prison, I would not

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:19.450
have been able to achieve the
most difficult task in life,

00:11:19.450 --> 00:11:21.687
and that is changing yourself.

00:11:21.687 --> 00:11:23.270
And he said very
clearly, he would not

00:11:23.270 --> 00:11:26.190
have been able to lead
South Africa to peace,

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:27.700
unless he'd been in prison.

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:29.770
He broke through a
problem and turned it

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:31.790
into an opportunity,
a possibility.

00:11:31.790 --> 00:11:37.442
Inside him-- not
immediately, but over time.

00:11:37.442 --> 00:11:39.275
So the bottom line is,
change is relentless.

00:11:39.275 --> 00:11:40.340
We know that.

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:42.330
It's happening all the time.

00:11:42.330 --> 00:11:44.530
But you either fit the
world as it changes,

00:11:44.530 --> 00:11:45.580
or you no longer fit.

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:49.090
You have a mismatch
between you and the world.

00:11:49.090 --> 00:11:53.450
And that's where things fail--
when there's a mismatch.

00:11:53.450 --> 00:11:57.370
So by understanding how
breakthroughs occur,

00:11:57.370 --> 00:11:59.840
you and me and other
people who understand

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:04.480
that anatomy can turn any
problem into possibility at

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:05.080
will.

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:05.913
And that's what I'm about.

00:12:05.913 --> 00:12:08.371
I'm in the business of helping
and empowering and inspiring

00:12:08.371 --> 00:12:10.120
guiding people to
be able to take

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:14.220
any problem-- from
their loved one dying,

00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:17.120
to an addiction you've
got, to a business

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:20.650
that's failing or starting the
beginning to fade away-- brand,

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:23.730
in a problem, or whatever--
and understanding

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:27.240
what you have to do to
be part of the future,

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:29.829
and not fail because
you're stuck in the past.

00:12:29.829 --> 00:12:30.620
That's my business.

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:32.036
So I'm hoping by
the end of today,

00:12:32.036 --> 00:12:34.620
you'll have a bit more
insight into that.

00:12:34.620 --> 00:12:36.630
So the bottom line
about creativity

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:38.840
is it's not quite
what we think it is.

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:39.590
So there's a myth.

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:42.660
There's a myth that
creativity is linear.

00:12:42.660 --> 00:12:45.630
What I mean by linear is,
you start with a solution--

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:47.640
I'm sorry, a problem.

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:50.691
And it's a low, kind
of level of disorder.

00:12:50.691 --> 00:12:51.940
There's something a bit wrong.

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:53.110
It's not quite good enough.

00:12:53.110 --> 00:12:56.920
You're surviving, it's not
quite where you want to be.

00:12:56.920 --> 00:12:59.010
And you walk along
a nice linear line,

00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:01.440
making it better,
bit by bit by bit.

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:03.142
And out comes a solution.

00:13:03.142 --> 00:13:04.350
What does that remind you of?

00:13:06.940 --> 00:13:08.179
A machine.

00:13:08.179 --> 00:13:09.220
That's how machines work.

00:13:09.220 --> 00:13:12.470
You put your foot on the
gas pedal of the car,

00:13:12.470 --> 00:13:14.370
and there is a
linear relationship

00:13:14.370 --> 00:13:20.300
between how much you
push, and how fast you go.

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:21.680
But in life, that's
not the case.

00:13:21.680 --> 00:13:23.510
You can work really
hard at a problem.

00:13:23.510 --> 00:13:26.480
You can go to
therapy for 10 years,

00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:29.640
and still not have broken
through the problem,

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:32.640
because breakthrough is
non-linear, because we

00:13:32.640 --> 00:13:36.330
are organisms, not algorithms.

00:13:36.330 --> 00:13:41.840
We are fundamentally wet,
hot, biological creatures.

00:13:41.840 --> 00:13:45.380
And in fact, if you
go into the brain,

00:13:45.380 --> 00:13:48.020
something astonishing happens
when people being creative.

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:50.145
So this is actually research
only a couple of years

00:13:50.145 --> 00:13:51.260
old, 18 months old.

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:53.970
They put rappers
into fMRI scanners

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:57.040
and asked them to
do different things.

00:13:57.040 --> 00:14:00.954
Group A-- read lyrics
you've already created.

00:14:00.954 --> 00:14:02.220
Right?

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:03.790
Go through the motions.

00:14:03.790 --> 00:14:06.700
Being present, being cool,
delivering, performing.

00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:08.130
But you've created the lyrics.

00:14:08.130 --> 00:14:10.710
Or free-style.

00:14:10.710 --> 00:14:13.660
And the fascinating
thing is, in the brain

00:14:13.660 --> 00:14:16.602
of the people,
rappers, free-styling,

00:14:16.602 --> 00:14:18.060
the area of the
brain that we think

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:22.439
is where all our
brilliant human reason

00:14:22.439 --> 00:14:24.230
comes from, the prefrontal
cortex the thing

00:14:24.230 --> 00:14:26.313
that's the biggest in
humans-- this whole bit here

00:14:26.313 --> 00:14:29.010
which makes us so clever, right?

00:14:29.010 --> 00:14:31.870
The kind of Greek idea of the
reason being this big shining

00:14:31.870 --> 00:14:35.990
light of truth becomes
less active when

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:39.720
you are spontaneously creating.

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:42.500
You have less control,
not more control.

00:14:42.500 --> 00:14:45.150
Less prefrontal
arousal a defocusing,

00:14:45.150 --> 00:14:48.620
not a focusing on the task
at hand, a defocusing away

00:14:48.620 --> 00:14:50.800
from the problem.

00:14:50.800 --> 00:14:55.140
The hub structures that keep
the brain all nicely regulated,

00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:57.580
if you like, start to
disintegrate, which again,

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:00.160
recent research from Imperial,
the same thing happens

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:02.700
when people take psychedelics,
the hub structures start

00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:05.020
to disintegrate,
more creativity.

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:06.570
And the brain starts
cycling really

00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:09.920
fast between active,
passive, active, passive.

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:14.080
In other words, you are
less smart-- technically,

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:16.150
traditionally,
conventionally, smart--

00:15:16.150 --> 00:15:20.400
when you're creating
than when you're not.

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:23.140
It's a big thing to
remember in a world

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:30.240
where we are usually awarded for
being clever in a linear way.

00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:36.340
Pushing the sales 3%
more, pushing the brand,

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:39.050
measures, 10% more,
whatever that is.

00:15:39.050 --> 00:15:40.690
Right?

00:15:40.690 --> 00:15:43.260
So what you realize is
that creativity is not

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:47.190
a straight line, it's
actually a curve.

00:15:47.190 --> 00:15:48.520
It's a J-shaped curve.

00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:53.480
You start with the
problem, then you go down

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:56.740
and you start having beginnings
of ideas that may or may not

00:15:56.740 --> 00:15:58.050
work.

00:15:58.050 --> 00:16:01.770
And then eventually, you
get a solution at the top.

00:16:01.770 --> 00:16:04.210
And the solution is
usually a lot better

00:16:04.210 --> 00:16:05.660
than the problem was.

00:16:05.660 --> 00:16:07.510
But you don't get there
until you go down.

00:16:07.510 --> 00:16:08.830
So I want to unpack
this for you now,

00:16:08.830 --> 00:16:10.110
because this is one of the
most important things I've ever

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:11.710
learned in my life.

00:16:11.710 --> 00:16:13.400
Just bear in mind,
I've run probably

00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:18.290
150 to 200 world-class
innovation projects designed

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:21.200
brief, specifically to come
up with big new business model

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:23.077
ideas, usually.

00:16:23.077 --> 00:16:25.160
And this is always the
process, and there's always

00:16:25.160 --> 00:16:28.290
a period here, where the client
says, so what's the solution?

00:16:28.290 --> 00:16:30.050
I go, I don't know.

00:16:30.050 --> 00:16:30.690
No one knows.

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:32.660
If we knew, it
would be creativity.

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:36.450
We just do the thing
we already knew.

00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:40.350
And companies don't like
this, for obvious reasons.

00:16:40.350 --> 00:16:41.610
People don't like it, either.

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:43.620
And we'll come on to
more about why that is.

00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:45.770
So what happens is,
as the world changes,

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:51.020
we notice a mismatch between
us or enterprise in the world.

00:16:51.020 --> 00:16:54.470
So you might have noticed a
mismatch recently in Apple

00:16:54.470 --> 00:16:55.356
and the world, OK?

00:16:55.356 --> 00:16:57.230
There are things Apple
are doing that are not

00:16:57.230 --> 00:16:59.320
matching where the world is.

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:02.820
They spent 20 years being
ahead of where the world is,

00:17:02.820 --> 00:17:05.660
and now I sense they're
starting to come behind

00:17:05.660 --> 00:17:09.130
where the world is in
various different areas.

00:17:09.130 --> 00:17:10.329
I can sense it.

00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:12.650
I'm sure many people do.

00:17:12.650 --> 00:17:14.630
So when you switch
on, you consciously

00:17:14.630 --> 00:17:18.099
decide to go into that
state to spontaneity,

00:17:18.099 --> 00:17:21.670
where the brain is less
controlled than it was before,

00:17:21.670 --> 00:17:23.020
which increases your creativity.

00:17:23.020 --> 00:17:25.329
And that can be done
over a few series

00:17:25.329 --> 00:17:29.010
of workshops or meditations or
coaching sessions, whatever.

00:17:29.010 --> 00:17:30.701
Then you have your breakthrough.

00:17:30.701 --> 00:17:32.200
Then you come up
with lots of ideas,

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:34.580
usually driven by purpose,
which is a big idea

00:17:34.580 --> 00:17:36.330
and it's really
important to understand

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:39.350
what your purpose is, what
this organization's purpose is.

00:17:39.350 --> 00:17:41.730
Then you start to rewire
yourself over time.

00:17:41.730 --> 00:17:43.912
It takes a long
time, it's not easy.

00:17:43.912 --> 00:17:45.370
This is just one
part of the thing.

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:47.172
The breakthrough
is the easy bit.

00:17:47.172 --> 00:17:49.630
Building it into your business,
building it into your life,

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:52.550
is where things get
really challenging.

00:17:52.550 --> 00:17:55.100
And then you get the
results you are looking for.

00:17:55.100 --> 00:17:57.590
Has anyone actually
recognized this experience

00:17:57.590 --> 00:18:01.680
in a transformation they've ever
had in their life in any area?

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:04.415
That things got
difficult first-- maybe

00:18:04.415 --> 00:18:07.720
you had burnout, stress,
worried, you freaked out,

00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:09.870
you left your job,
the project collapsed.

00:18:09.870 --> 00:18:13.020
And then something came
out and you followed it,

00:18:13.020 --> 00:18:16.824
and then you build something
new over long period of time.

00:18:16.824 --> 00:18:17.990
And finally you got the win.

00:18:20.417 --> 00:18:22.000
And that's what this
win is here, what

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:23.291
I call the thrive differential.

00:18:23.291 --> 00:18:25.510
The ability-- the amount
you're willing to go down

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:27.230
to get the up.

00:18:27.230 --> 00:18:29.740
I believe that will predict
the quality of your life

00:18:29.740 --> 00:18:30.730
in the future.

00:18:30.730 --> 00:18:33.280
How much you're willing
to lose control, to let

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:35.400
go, to get that.

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:38.141
Because the other option
is, you notice the mismatch,

00:18:38.141 --> 00:18:40.640
you don't do anything about it,
you try and stay in control,

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:42.850
you try to keep your shit
together and stuff down.

00:18:42.850 --> 00:18:44.710
I'm not going to change.

00:18:44.710 --> 00:18:46.320
I don't care that
my world's moving on

00:18:46.320 --> 00:18:47.819
and my relationship
are failing, I'm

00:18:47.819 --> 00:18:51.270
just going to hunker down and
hope it all changes around me.

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:54.031
They have to change, not me.

00:18:54.031 --> 00:18:55.030
Stuck in a comfort zone.

00:18:55.030 --> 00:18:56.930
The world moves on.

00:18:56.930 --> 00:18:57.874
You become irrelevant.

00:18:57.874 --> 00:18:59.290
The enterprise
becomes irrelevant.

00:18:59.290 --> 00:19:01.430
And you enter a
breakdown, ultimately.

00:19:01.430 --> 00:19:03.180
Which can look like
something spectacular,

00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:05.055
like mine, when I burnt
out and couldn't even

00:19:05.055 --> 00:19:06.160
go to work for a year.

00:19:06.160 --> 00:19:09.750
Or, it can look like a
slow decay of a business

00:19:09.750 --> 00:19:12.970
and gets bought by someone else.

00:19:12.970 --> 00:19:14.580
Various ways of doing.

00:19:14.580 --> 00:19:16.107
So here's the
individual version,

00:19:16.107 --> 00:19:17.940
which is what's in the
book, these 10 steps.

00:19:17.940 --> 00:19:20.090
Each chapter in the
book is one step.

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:21.980
And this is my one
example for me.

00:19:21.980 --> 00:19:23.020
I had this burnout.

00:19:23.020 --> 00:19:24.290
Big problem.

00:19:24.290 --> 00:19:25.150
But I went into it.

00:19:25.150 --> 00:19:26.816
I was like, why is
this happening to me?

00:19:26.816 --> 00:19:29.040
Why I have some kind of
low-level clinical depression

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:34.150
stress, up and down mood
swings, since I was 14, 15?

00:19:34.150 --> 00:19:35.982
Went into it.

00:19:35.982 --> 00:19:37.940
I realized a couple of
really important things.

00:19:37.940 --> 00:19:39.570
I was running a great company.

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:40.750
I had 50 staff.

00:19:40.750 --> 00:19:42.790
I was multimillion paper.

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:45.820
I had gold cards of every
description, black cards.

00:19:45.820 --> 00:19:47.117
Whatever's going on.

00:19:47.117 --> 00:19:48.700
But it was built
around something that

00:19:48.700 --> 00:19:49.850
wasn't that wasn't my purpose.

00:19:49.850 --> 00:19:51.516
It was built around
my ego and my desire

00:19:51.516 --> 00:19:52.760
to be rich and famous.

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:54.750
And it just wasn't
working for me.

00:19:54.750 --> 00:19:57.690
But more than that, I realized
I was building a business

00:19:57.690 --> 00:20:02.510
around using my talents
and transformation to find

00:20:02.510 --> 00:20:07.030
the part of you as consumers
where you are feeling

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:12.010
a little weak, a little
unsure, flick it, and say

00:20:12.010 --> 00:20:17.240
if you buy this product we just
invented, you'll be all right.

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:19.710
And it kind of moment
of huge discovery,

00:20:19.710 --> 00:20:23.070
I realized that I had to
flip that, and use my skills

00:20:23.070 --> 00:20:25.610
and transformation in
creativity and breakthrough

00:20:25.610 --> 00:20:28.674
to persuade everyone that
by going inside and dealing

00:20:28.674 --> 00:20:30.840
with yourself, you will
realize that you are already

00:20:30.840 --> 00:20:32.300
absolutely enough.

00:20:32.300 --> 00:20:35.010
And with that abundance
of creativity,

00:20:35.010 --> 00:20:38.630
you can go about making
the world a better place.

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:40.970
Because people who are
living in stress and in fear

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:43.700
tend not to be able to go out
and solve their communities'

00:20:43.700 --> 00:20:45.320
problems.

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:47.600
The two things are interrelated.

00:20:47.600 --> 00:20:49.865
So I realized I had a broken
heart with my own career.

00:20:49.865 --> 00:20:51.990
I'd built a company that
was breaking my own heart.

00:20:51.990 --> 00:20:54.380
I wanted to be a psychiatrist,
and I'm now doing

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:55.500
marketing and advertising.

00:20:55.500 --> 00:20:57.590
I mean, it's like a total flip.

00:20:57.590 --> 00:20:59.186
So I unwound the whole thing.

00:20:59.186 --> 00:21:00.560
I exited my own
company, which is

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:04.990
kind of crazy-- without
the money, by the way.

00:21:04.990 --> 00:21:09.850
Much to the chagrin out of
my accountant and my family.

00:21:09.850 --> 00:21:10.850
They thought I was nuts.

00:21:10.850 --> 00:21:12.850
Bear in mind, I'd already
left a medical career.

00:21:12.850 --> 00:21:16.720
a high-flying medical
career at Cambridge, at UCL.

00:21:16.720 --> 00:21:18.780
So there's this Jewish
family, first child

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:21.721
to go into university,
and they're like, oh,

00:21:21.721 --> 00:21:24.220
but you left med-- but then you
got this business thing, OK.

00:21:24.220 --> 00:21:25.070
Now what are you doing?

00:21:25.070 --> 00:21:26.861
You're 30 years old,
and now you don't even

00:21:26.861 --> 00:21:29.780
have the business you
just built. Right?

00:21:29.780 --> 00:21:33.030
That's the reality of
when you change things.

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:35.100
And then I have
now worked out how

00:21:35.100 --> 00:21:37.670
to build two businesses
around my purpose.

00:21:37.670 --> 00:21:40.225
But I'm no longer in
the official world's way

00:21:40.225 --> 00:21:41.100
of looking at things.

00:21:41.100 --> 00:21:42.980
My business is no
longer worth anything

00:21:42.980 --> 00:21:45.760
like my first business was.

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:50.050
But I'm thriving, at the
edge of my life in all areas.

00:21:50.050 --> 00:21:51.690
And that is priceless.

00:21:51.690 --> 00:21:54.826
And here's the version
we use for companies.

00:21:54.826 --> 00:21:56.200
Here's a very
clever tool that we

00:21:56.200 --> 00:21:58.304
use to break through
corporate problems.

00:21:58.304 --> 00:22:00.220
And here's the version
we use in storytelling,

00:22:00.220 --> 00:22:02.550
which is another area
where this comes out.

00:22:05.420 --> 00:22:09.570
So I have now begun to find
this J-curve everywhere.

00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:12.119
And I'm actually developing
another book on this topic,

00:22:12.119 --> 00:22:12.910
about this J-curve.

00:22:12.910 --> 00:22:13.240
What is it?

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:15.190
Because I've found it
in chemical reactions,

00:22:15.190 --> 00:22:16.770
learning curves,
narrative structure.

00:22:16.770 --> 00:22:20.290
All Hollywood scripts
follow this J-curve.

00:22:20.290 --> 00:22:23.544
Not usually Danish outre movies.

00:22:23.544 --> 00:22:25.585
They sort of come down
here, and come round there

00:22:25.585 --> 00:22:27.740
and leave you going, I
don't know where I am.

00:22:27.740 --> 00:22:28.615
A couple investment.

00:22:28.615 --> 00:22:30.030
You invest in a company.

00:22:30.030 --> 00:22:31.770
It loses money.

00:22:31.770 --> 00:22:34.180
Hopefully it starts to
make money and come out,

00:22:34.180 --> 00:22:36.680
but it's a big risk, as we
know from the VC industry.

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:39.640
Scientific revolutions,
if anyone read any Kuhn,

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:40.830
follow the same thing.

00:22:40.830 --> 00:22:42.880
Political change,
if you're Egypt,

00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:45.700
you're in democracy-- you're
not in democracy with Mubarak.

00:22:45.700 --> 00:22:48.760
You want to be a stable
democracy like America,

00:22:48.760 --> 00:22:50.609
but it's not going
to be linear, guys.

00:22:50.609 --> 00:22:52.150
You're going to have
to disintegrate.

00:22:52.150 --> 00:22:53.524
And that's what's
happening here.

00:22:53.524 --> 00:22:59.170
